{"label":"Redux JS - Intro","id":"reduxjs","list":[{"label":"Multiple Choice Question","type":"mcq","id":"test","commonData":{"title":"Multiple Choice Question","allowFrac":false},"data":[{"questions":[{"qText":"What is Redux mainly used for?","options":"State management\n              Styling React components\nHandling HTTP requests\nAnimations"},{"qText":"Redux follows which architectural pattern?","options":"Flux\n              MVC\nMVVM\nSingleton"},{"qText":"In Redux, the state of the application is stored in a _____.","options":"Store\n              Reducer\nComponent\nAction"},{"qText":"Which of the following is true about Redux?","options":"It uses a single centralized store\n              It allows multiple stores per application\nIt stores data only in local storage"},{"qText":"In Redux, how are state updates triggered?","options":"By dispatching actions\n              By directly changing the store\nBy modifying reducers directly\nBy updating React props"}]},{"questions":[{"qText":"Actions in Redux are represented as _____.","options":"Plain JavaScript objects\n              Strings only\nFunctions only\nReact components"},{"qText":"Which property is mandatory in a Redux action object?","options":"type\n              id\npayload\nreducer"},{"qText":"Reducers in Redux must be _____.","options":"Pure functions\n              Asynchronous functions\nSide-effect functions \nRecursive functions"},{"qText":"What does the 'combineReducers' function do in Redux?","options":"Combines multiple reducers into one root reducer\n              Creates multiple stores\nSplits actions into smaller parts\nMerges states automatically"},{"qText":"Which method is used to send an action to the Redux store?","options":"dispatch()\n              send()\ncall()\ntrigger()"}]},{"questions":[{"qText":"What is the default state parameter in a reducer function usually set to?","options":"An initial state value\n              null\nundefined\nA function"},{"qText":"Which library is commonly used with Redux to connect React components to the store?","options":"react-redux\n              react-router\nredux-saga\nreact-dom"},{"qText":"Which Redux middleware is used for handling asynchronous operations like API calls?","options":"redux-thunk\nredux-saga\n* Both\nNone"},{"qText":"In Redux, the mapStateToProps function is used to _____.","options":"Connect state from the store to component props\n              Dispatch actions\nCreate reducers\nReplace the store"},{"qText":"Redux ensures that state is _____.","options":"Immutable and centralized\n              Mutable and centralized\nMutable and decentralized\nPrivate to each component"}]}]},{"label":"Drag and Drop","id":"dragdrop","type":"matchByDragDrop","data":{"fontSize":"1.3rem","dashWidth":80,"text":"Central object that holds the entire state of the application : *Store*\nA plain JavaScript object that describes what happened (has a type) : *Action*\nA pure function that takes state + action and returns new state : *Reducer*\nFunction used to send an action to the Redux store : *Dispatch*\nReact-Redux hook used to access values from the store's state : *useSelector*\nReact-Redux hook used to dispatch actions from components : *useDispatch*\nProvides a way to extend Redux with custom functionality (e.g., logging, async) : *Middleware*\nHelper function to merge multiple reducers into one : *combineReducers*"}},{"type":"classifySentence","label":"True or False","id":"true-false","data":{"title":"True or False","types":[{"name":"True","text":"Redux is a state management library often used with React.\n            Actions in Redux must always be plain JavaScript objects.\n            Reducers in Redux are pure functions, meaning they should not mutate the state directly.\n            Redux middleware like 'redux-thunk' and 'redux-saga' are used to handle asynchronous tasks.\n            The 'dispatch()' function is used to send actions to the store.\n            The state in Redux is immutable, meaning new state objects are created instead of modifying the old one.\n            react-redux is a library that helps connect React components to the Redux store."},{"name":"False","text":"In Redux, multiple stores can exist in a single application.\n            The 'type' property in an action object is optional.\n            'combineReducers' is used to merge multiple stores into one.\n            "}]}},{"id":"fillup","label":"Fill in the blanks","type":"fillup","data":{"title":"Fill in the blanks","fontSize":"1.4rem","text":"In Redux, the application state is stored in a *Store (Reducer, Component) * .\n        The function used to send actions to the Redux store is *dispatch (trigger, send) * .\n        Every Redux action must have a *type (payload, reducer) * property.\n        Reducers in Redux must be *pure (asynchronous, recursive)* functions.\n        The function used to combine multiple reducers into one is *combineReducers(mergeReducers, joinReducers)*.\n        To connect Redux with React, we commonly use the *react-redux (react-router, redux-saga)* library.\n        The middleware often used for handling async logic like API calls is *redux-thunk (react-redux, redux-form)*.\n        In Redux, state should be treated as *immutable (mutable, temporary) *.\n        The function used to read state from the Redux store is *getState (fetchState, readState)* .\n        The function that maps state from the Redux store to React component props is called *mapStateToProps (mapDispatchToProps, connectState) *."}}]}